frameDefinitions: A trial is a process conducted in a Court before a Judge and (usually) a Jury in which the participants meet in order to decide a Case.
The  Speaker expresses through language his wish to get the Addressee to act in some way that will help to bring about events or states described in the Content.

This frame consists of words that describe a hostile encounter between opposing forces (Side_1 and Side_2, collectively conceptualizable as Sides) over a disputed Issue and/or in order to reach a specific  Purpose. '' 'He still wants to fight Mike Tyson in about 8 months.'
A group of Arguers (also expressible as Arguer1 and Arguer2) express incompatible opinions or beliefs about an Issue.

This frame is concerned with the idea that people (Participant_1, Participant_2, or Participants) participate in an organized, rule-governed activity (the Competition) in order to achieve some advantageous outcome (often the Prize).
An Assailant physically attacks a Victim (which is usually but not always sentient), causing or intending to cause the Victim physical damage.
frameExamples: Mr Smithers always <t>encourages</t> the employees to stay late and work harder.
He still wants to <t>fight</t> Mike Tyson in about 8 months.
We <t>bickered</t> about semantics for an hour.
As soon as he stepped out of the bar he was <t>set</t> upon by four men in ski-masks.
